<div class="row article-content_item js-articleContent "><div class="col-d12 col-t12"><div class="review-box section-bordered-both spacer-top-30"><figure class="u-left spacer-right-20"><a rel="nofollow" href="http://ai.christianitytoday.com/cti/adclick/fcid=/random=15438939/site=ctmag/area=article/position=/category=/relocate=https://www.amazon.com/dp/080215770X?tag=christtoday-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1" target="_blank"><img src="https://m.media-amazon.com/images/I/51WM1pn+2iL._SX140.jpg" alt="Girl, Woman, Other: A Novel (Booker Prize Winner)" title="Girl, Woman, Other: A Novel (Booker Prize Winner)" width="140" itemprop="image" /></a></figure><div class="review-box-content"><div class="d-flex align-items-center spacer-bottom-10"><span class="headings-small heading uppercase">Our Rating</span><div class="reviewDesc" itemprop="reviewRating"><img src="/system/img/stars-4.gif" width="75" height="14" title="4 Stars - Excellent" alt="4 Stars - Excellent" /></div>
</div>
<div class="d-flex align-items-center spacer-bottom-10"><span class="headings-small heading uppercase">Book Title</span><div class="reviewDesc" itemprop="name">Girl, Woman, Other: A Novel (Booker Prize Winner)</div>
</div>
<div class="d-flex align-items-center spacer-bottom-10"><span class="headings-small heading uppercase">Author</span><div class="reviewDesc" itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"></div>
</div>
<div class="d-flex align-items-center spacer-bottom-10"><span class="headings-small heading uppercase">Publisher</span><div class="reviewDesc">Grove Press</div>
</div>
<div class="d-flex align-items-center spacer-bottom-10"><span class="headings-small heading uppercase">Release Date</span><div class="reviewDesc" itemprop="v.	datePublished">December 2, 2019</div>
</div>
<div class="d-flex align-items-center spacer-bottom-10"><span class="headings-small heading uppercase">Pages</span><div class="ratingTxt">464</div>
</div>
<figure><a href="http://ai.christianitytoday.com/cti/adclick/fcid=/random=15438939/site=ctmag/area=article/position=/category=/relocate=https://www.amazon.com/dp/080215770X?tag=christtoday-20&linkCode=ogi&th=1&psc=1" target="_blank"><img src="/ct/channel/img/btn_buy_amazon.gif" width="140" height="25" alt="Buy Girl, Woman, Other: A Novel (Booker Prize Winner) from Amazon" title="Buy Girl, Woman, Other: A Novel (Booker Prize Winner) from Amazon" /></a></figure></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="col-d12 col-t12"><div class="body-content u-right spacer-top-30"><div class="article-body spacer-right-40"><div id="body" class="paywall content-body"><p class="text"><span class="dropcap">W</span>e read to know we&rsquo;re not alone.&rdquo; These words, taken from William Nicholson&rsquo;s play <span class="citation">Shadowlands</span>, capture our deep motivation to read. When we read, we see life through another&rsquo;s eyes, sometimes recognizing our <em>own</em> desires, dreams, and disappointments. It&rsquo;s like the feeling of a friend&rsquo;s arm, silently extended around your shoulders. You&rsquo;re not alone.</p>
<p class="text">But as Christians, we are called to more than this. We&rsquo;re called not to comfort ourselves but to discomfort ourselves. We&rsquo;re called&mdash;like the Good Samaritan&mdash;to stop in the wayside world of the other, especially others who are least like ourselves. And sometimes, the passport to that world is a book.</p>
<h4 class="subhead">Playful Complexities</h4>
<p class="text"><span class="citation">Girl, Woman, Other </span>is a 2019 Booker Prize&ndash;winning novel by Bernardine Evaristo, whose works experiment with prose and verse and explore the African diaspora. The book is set in London, my hometown. I recognize its places, streets, and turns of phrase. But its 12 protagonists could hardly be more different from me. Most were born in poverty. Most experiment sexually. All live as black or brown women in majority-white contexts. One whose faith had carried her through trials felt that faith die along with her beloved husband. (It was buried when her prosperity-gospel pastor traded sex for a small business loan.) But even across these differences, Evaristo conjures empathy with a magician&rsquo;s flare. Indeed, the book is structured around empathy.</p>
<p class="text">Chapters 1 to 4 narrate 12 women&rsquo;s tales, in clusters of three. For example, chapter 1 gives us the keys first to Amma&rsquo;s inner thoughts, then to those of her daughter, Yazz, and finally to those of her best friend, Dominique. We learn each woman from the inside out, but we also see them from the outside in. The effect is a sustained soliloquy, as actor after actor takes the stage. Time and again, the other becomes the self.</p>
<p class="text">As a white, British woman, I emerged from this book with a richer understanding of the range of experiences of black and brown women in my country&mdash;not least the hurt and the heartbreak. Despite addressing issues as serious as rape and emotional abuse, and topics as fraught as gender, cultural origin, immigrant status, and sexual experience, Evaristo is never monochrome or preachy. She highlights the complexities at play while being playful with complexity.</p>
<p class="text">One example of this playfulness is Evaristo&rsquo;s portrayal of Nzinga, an African-American &ldquo;builder of timber houses on &lsquo;wimmin&rsquo;s lands&rsquo; in the &lsquo;Dis-United States of America,&rsquo;&rdquo; with whom Dominique falls deeply in love. When Dominique first brings Nzinga to meet her best friend Amma, Nzinga opines on what black women should and shouldn&rsquo;t do, including not wearing black socks or underpants or using black garbage bags. As Evaristo tells it, &ldquo;Amma kept flashing Dominique looks, is she serious? are <em>you </em>serious?&rdquo; But Dominique is lapping it up.</p>
<p class="text">We&rsquo;ve all seen friends imbibe nonsense from those they adore. If we&rsquo;re honest, we&rsquo;ve probably done that ourselves. But the comedy of this moment becomes poignant as we witness Nzinga shrinking Dominique&rsquo;s world down, inch by inch, to an abusive cage, from which Amma ultimately helps her escape. Evaristo&rsquo;s characters have flaws and foibles, and intermural fights, and we see how love and politics get tangled up. But even as we are struck by difference, we&rsquo;re also invited to identify.</p>
<p class="text">Some of Evaristo&rsquo;s most powerful moments knock at generational walls. Amma is not the conventional sort. An iconoclastic black, lesbian, feminist playwright, she is also deliberately promiscuous. Yet the Amma with whom Evaristo leaves us when she quietly passes the mic to Amma&rsquo;s daughter, Yazz, is filled with conventional feelings. She&rsquo;s realized her dead father, whose traditional thinking she despised, was &ldquo;a good man.&rdquo; She&rsquo;s started trying to police her daughter&rsquo;s clothes. And she has suffered that same daughter&rsquo;s rejection of her most deeply held beliefs:</p><div class="align-center spacer-bottom-15 clearfix"><span class="article-divider">Article continues below</span><div class="spacer-bottom-20 clearfix bg-ad-gray "><figure>
<script type="text/javascript">
if (!pageNum) { var pageNum = Math.round(Math.random() * 100000000); }
document.write('<scr'); 
